               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450407-name-1309" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1309" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1309" type="surname" value="ADAMS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1309" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD ADAMS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am watchman to Mr. Henry Philip Davis—he had a barge with coals in it. off Palace-yard, Lambeth—that is the barge the officer saw—the coals in it were my master's.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450407-name-1310" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1310" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1310" type="surname" value="FROST"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1310" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES FROST</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable L</hi> 59.) I was on duty about eight o'clock in the evening, on the 25th of March, in Palace-yard, Lambeth—I saw the prisoner by the side of Mr. Davis's barge—I saw Heath lift Wright into the barge, and Wright rolled some coals to the side, he gave them to Heath, who took them, and they were removed fifteen of sixteen yards from the barge.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Heath.</hi> I was going over the water, and when I got there, the officer took me; this little boy could not lift the coals; they weighed 601bs. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> One coal weighed 60 lbs., Wright rolled to the side, and Heath took it down.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Wright.</hi> I was not near the barge.</p>
               <p>
